Graph Basics

What is a Graph?

    A Graph is a non-linear data structure used to represent relationships between objects.

A graph consists of:

    Vertices (Nodes) → Entities/Objects
    Edges → Connections between vertices

Terminology

    Vertex (Node) - A point in the graph.
    Edge - A connection between two vertices.
    Degree - Number of edges connected to a vertex.
    Path - A sequence of vertices connected by edges.
    Cycle - A path that starts and ends at the same vertex.

    Connected Graph - Every vertex can be reached from every other vertex.
                    - All nodes are connected.
    
    Disconnected Graph - Some vertices cannot be reached.
                       - Two separate components.

Types of Graphs

    1. Undirected Graph - Edges have no direction.
                        - You can travel both ways.
    
    2. Directed Graph (Digraph) - Edges have direction.
    3. Weighted Graph - Edges contain weights (cost, distance, time).
    4. Unweighted Graph - No weights on edges.

Graph Representation

    1. Adjacency Matrix
    2. Adjacency List

Graph Traversal

    1. Breadth First Search (BFS)
    2. Depth First Search (DFS)
